Caity Matter finished with 24 points
Friday night to lead No. 22 Ohio State over 18th-ranked Minnesota
58-50 in the quarterfinals of the Big Ten tournament.
article.headline: McCarville tallies triple-double in losing effort
article.linkText: McCarville hits triple-double, but Minnesota falls in Big Ten
article.story:
INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- When Caity Matter finally started scoring,
her points came in a hurry.

Scoring in bunches in each half, Matter finished with 24 points
Friday night to lead Ohio (No. 22 AP) State over Minnesota (No. 17 ESPN/USA Today; No. 18 AP) 58-50 in the quarterfinals of the Big Ten tournament.

"I think early on I was not being aggressive in getting my shot
or shooting threes," Matter said. "I think it was something I was
doing and I had to change that."

Minnesota cut a nine-point lead to three in the closing minutes,
but Matter scored the next 10 points for the Buckeyes, finishing
with two free throws for a 56-50 lead with 36 seconds to go.
Brandie Hoskins gave Ohio State (20-8) its final basket on a fast
break after the Gophers' 22nd turnover.

"We had to get a win even though it was kind of ugly," Matter
said. "We pulled it out and we were aggressive in the end."

The Buckeyes moved into the tournament semifinals for a rematch
Sunday against No. 6 Purdue, which beat them for the championship
last year. Purdue advanced with a 78-55 victory over Michigan.

"I think we've matured a great deal and we're better equipped
to handle ugly games," Ohio State coach Jim Foster said. "It's
great when everything is going in and it's pretty, but I think ugly
games determine your season."

Janel McCarville led Minnesota (21-8) with 23 points, 11
rebounds and a career-high 10 steals -- the first triple-double in
tourney history.

"I thought we came in as underdogs and we played like it. We
played like we had nothing to lose," McCarville said. "Coach said
in the locker room that she didn't think we could do much more
other than put the ball in the basket a couple more times."

Minnesota coach Pam Borton said McCarville "played like she was
on a mission."

"She did everything our team needed her do and brought a lot of
energy and emotion," Borton said. "Obviously, we're disappointed
to lose the basketball game, but I thought it was a great game."

Matter, Ohio State's scoring leader this season, kept the
Buckeyes in front with two big runs, including 10 of her team's
final 13 points of the first half and 12 of the final 18 in the
second.

Minnesota, which started the season 15-0, lost five of its eight
games since career scoring leader Lindsay Whalen broke her hand
against Ohio State last month. Without her 21 points a game, the
only consistent scorer was McCarville, who had the first five
points for Minnesota and 11 of the Gophers' 20 in the first half.

"We wanted to put pressure on the basketball," Borton said.
"We played the passing lanes well and made them work for every
single basket they got."

Minnesota's last lead was at 16-14 on a basket by McCarville,
then Matter hit two straight 3-pointers to start the Buckeyes'
first big run at the end of the half. After a basket by Kadidja
Andersson pulled Minnesota within three points, Matter scored again
on a fast break and Jessica Davenport added another basket for a
27-20 lead at halftime.

The Gophers got to 44-41 on a basket by Andersson, but Davenport
scored and Matter hit another 3-pointer as Ohio State pulled away
for good.

Davenport finished with 10 points.
